			<ns0:name>phajdan.jr@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/phajdan.jr@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Currently the SDK sources are fetched from a larger checkout and they seem to be in a git repo.

This makes packaging (e.g. for Linux distributions) a huge pain, because the procedure of getting the sources is highly non-standard. It requires having a NaCl tree checkout, then running a command just to get full sources, and only then the thing can be built.

Please publish base version number of tools you use and patch (e.g. gcc-4.4.3, binutils-2.12.1) and *versioned* patches for those tools.

This should result in Linux distros including NaCl toolchain in their package systems, making it easier to built Chrome from source with NaCl support. Currently most from-source Chrome builds either do not support NaCl or are very painful to package.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-07-31T11:29:57.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2011-09-29T21:41:33.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:state>closed</ns2:state><ns0:title>Publish NaCl toolchain sources as combination of base version numbers and patches</ns0:title><ns2:label>Type-Enhancement</ns2:label><ns2:label>Pri-2</ns2:label><ns2:label>Component-Infrastructure</ns2:label><ns2:label>OS-All</ns2:label><ns2:label>CoreRuntime</ns2:label><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/2324/comments/full" rel="replies" type="application/atom+xml" /><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=2324" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/full/2324" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /><ns2:stars>3</ns2:stars><ns2:blocking>
